6:["$","section",null,{"className":"mb-12","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Rate Mechanics"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"Both exchanges use 8-hour funding intervals with similar calculation methods based on perpetual-spot price differences. Gate.io typically exhibits wider funding rate spreads due to its extensive micro-cap token coverage, creating more arbitrage opportunities on less liquid pairs. Bitget's growing market share has led to more stable funding rates on major pairs, while Gate.io's established user base maintains consistent funding flows across its broader token selection."}]]}]
7:["$","$Lb",null,{"items":[{"question":"Which exchange offers better funding arbitrage opportunities?","answer":"Gate.io provides more opportunities through its 1,700+ perpetual pairs including micro-caps, while Bitget offers more stable rates on major tokens. Gate.io's wider selection creates more pricing inefficiencies to exploit."},{"question":"How do the funding rate calculation methods differ?","answer":"Both use standard 8-hour intervals with mark price methodology, but Gate.io's broader token coverage leads to more volatile funding rates. Bitget's rates tend to be more predictable due to concentrated liquidity on popular pairs."},{"question":"Which platform has lower total arbitrage costs?","answer":"Gate.io has lower base fees at 0.015%/0.05% versus Bitget's 0.02%/0.06%. However, Bitget's better liquidity on major pairs can result in lower slippage costs for larger arbitrage positions."},{"question":"What are the key risk differences for funding arbitrage?","answer":"Gate.io carries higher execution risk on micro-cap pairs due to lower liquidity, while Bitget presents counterparty risk as a newer exchange. Gate.io's longer track record provides more operational stability for long-term strategies."}]}]
